The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, August 18, 2004 				 Airport update deal comes with strings
 OUR BUREAU																								New Delhi, Aug. 17: The private developer who wins the contract for the modernisation of Mumbai and Delhi airports will have to absorb at least 40 per cent of the existing employees at the airport.																								A group of ministers has decided that the joint venture company developing the two airports will be required to absorb a minimum of net 40 per cent of the existing employees at these airports. The employees who are not absorbed by the joint venture companies will revert to Airports Authority of India, minister of state for civil aviation Praful Patel said today.																								Foreign direct investment in airports has been capped at 49 per cent and at least 25 per cent of the equity in the joint venture group should be held by Indian entities. Besides, maximum permissible equity participation by Indian scheduled airlines has been increased from 5 to 10 per cent.																								Patel said 10 consortiums have bid for taking up Mumbai and Delhi airports.																								These include consortium of Bharti Enterprise-Singapore Changi airport, Videocon-Methven Corp, Hochtief Airport-Piramal Holding- amp;T, Macquarie Bank-Agarwal Galvanising-Aeroports de Paris, GMR Infrastructure-Fraport AG, Pan India Paryatan-TAV Investment Construction Corp, GVK Industries-Airports Company South Africa, DLF-Malaysia Airport, Reliance Airport and DS Construction-Flughafen Munchen of Munich. 
